04451nam a22007095i 9780801460333DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014603337 a10.7591/97808014603332doi  a(DE-B1597)480106  a(OCoLC)979833555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD804.7.M67bD43 2017 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.5318142231 aDean, Carolyn J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAversion and Erasure :bThe Fate of the Victim after the Holocaust /cCarolyn J. Dean. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Victims, Suffering, Identity -- t1. The Surfeit of Jewish Memory -- t2. French Discourses on Exorbitant Jewish Memory -- t3. Minimalism and Victim Testimony -- t4. Erasures -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Aversion and Erasure, Carolyn J. Dean offers a bold account of how the Holocaust's status as humanity's most terrible example of evil has shaped contemporary discourses about victims in the West. Popular and scholarly attention to the Holocaust has led some observers to conclude that a "surfeit of Jewish memory" is obscuring the suffering of other peoples. Dean explores the pervasive idea that suffering and trauma in the United States and Western Europe have become central to identity, with victims competing for recognition by displaying their collective wounds.She argues that this notion has never been examined systematically even though it now possesses the force of self-evidence. It developed in nascent form after World War II, when the near-annihilation of European Jewry began to transform patriotic mourning into a slogan of "Never Again": as the Holocaust demonstrated, all people might become victims because of their ethnicity, race, gender, or sexuality—because of who they are.The recent concept that suffering is central to identity and that Jewish suffering under Nazism is iconic of modern evil has dominated public discourse since the 1980s.Dean argues that we believe that the rational contestation of grievances in democratic societies is being replaced by the proclamation of injury and the desire to be a victim. Such dramatic and yet culturally powerful assertions, however, cast suspicion on victims and define their credibility in new ways that require analysis. Dean's latest book summons anyone concerned with human rights to recognize the impact of cultural ideals of "deserving" and "undeserving" victims on those who have suffered.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aVictims. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146033340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460333/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK